\\\":\\\"**Considering Spring Boot configuration**\\\\n\\\\nI'm thinking about whether we should prefer certain annotations in Spring Boot, particularly spring-boot-autoconfigure. It seems like a more direct approach might help us avoid potential issues with SpringApplication. But now I’m wondering: does AnnotationConfigApplicationContext automatically include ConfigurationPropertiesBindingPostProcessor? I recall that @EnableConfigurationProperties is what registers them. There could be some concerns with condition report classes, so it might be worth editing that aspect!\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_ACxA3fkV5n1yVEH3OfsWkmKh|fc_0898fde1534ab2a6016a0bdb11e0dc8194adfaa5659c93dd25\", \"name\": \"edit\", \"arguments\": {\"path\": \"tests/src/org.springframework.boot/spring-boot-jackson/4.0.2/src/test/java/org_springframework_boot/spring_boot_jackson/JacksonAutoConfigurationInnerAbstractMapperBuilderCustomizerTest.java\", \"edits\": [{\"oldText\": \"import org.springframework.boot.SpringApplication;\\nimport org.springframework.boot.WebApplicationType;\\nimport org.springframework.boot.jackson.autoconfigure.JacksonAutoConfiguration;\\nimport org.springframework.context.ConfigurableApplicationContext;\\n\", \"newText\": \"import org.springframework.boot.jackson.autoconfigure.JacksonAutoConfiguration;\\nimport org.springframework.context.annotation.AnnotationConfigApplicationContext;\\nimport org.springframework.core.env.MapPropertySource;\\n\"}, {\"oldText\": \"\\t\\tMap<String, Object> properties = Map.of(\\\"spring.jackson.find-and-add-modules\\\", \\\"false\\\",\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\\"spring.jackson.property-naming-strategy\\\", \\\"SNAKE_CASE\\\");\\n\\t\\tSpringApplication application = new SpringApplication(JacksonAutoConfiguration.class);\\n\\t\\tapplication.setWebApplicationType(WebApplicationType.NONE);\\n\\t\\tapplication.setDefaultProperties(properties);\\n\\n\\t\\ttry (ConfigurableApplicationContext context = application.run()) {\\n\\t\\t\\tJsonMapper mapper = context.getBean(JsonMapper.class);\\n\\n\\t\\t\\tassertThat(mapper.writeValueAsString(new SampleValue(\\\"Spring Boot\\\")))\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t.isEqualTo(\\\"{\\\\\\\"sample_name\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"Spring Boot\\\\\\\"}\\\");\\n\\t\\t}\\n\", \"newText\": \"\\t\\tMap<String, Object> properties = Map.of(\\\"spring.jackson.find-and-add-modules\\\", false,\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t\\\"spring.jackson.property-naming-strategy\\\", \\\"SNAKE_CASE\\\");\\n\\n\\t\\ttry (AnnotationConfigApplicationContext context = new AnnotationConfigApplicationContext()) {\\n\\t\\t\\tcontext.getEnvironment().getPropertySources().addFirst(new MapPropertySource(\\\"test\\\", properties));\\n\\t\\t\\tcontext.register(JacksonAutoConfiguration.class);\\n\\t\\t\\tcontext.refresh();\\n\\t\\t\\tJsonMapper mapper = context.getBean(JsonMapper.class);\\n\\n\\t\\t\\tassertThat(mapper.writeValueAsString(new SampleValue(\\\"Spring Boot\\\")))\\n\\t\\t\\t\\t.isEqualTo(\\\"{\\\\\\\"sample_name\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"Spring Boot\\\\\\\"}\\\");\\n\\t\\t}\\n\"}]}}], \"api\": \"openai-responses\", \"provider\": \"OCA\", \"model\": \"gpt-5.5\", \"usage\": {\"input\": 1025, \"output\": 1378, \"cacheRead\": 25088, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"totalTokens\": 27491, \"cost\": {\"input\": 0, \"output\": 0, \"cacheRead\": 0, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"total\": 0}}, \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\", \"timestamp\": 1779161858957, \"responseId\": \"resp_0898fde1534ab2a6016a0bdb03671c8194ab4035f83686f5c9\"}}\nhuman-intervention-logs/org.springframework.boot:spring-boot-jackson:4.0.2/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-05-19T03-38-03-995764Z.log:2065:[recv] {\"type\": \"turn_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Considering Spring Boot configuration**\\n\\nI'm thinking about whether we should prefer certain annotations in Spring Boot, particularly spring-boot-autoconfigure. It seems like a more direct approach might help us avoid potential issues with SpringApplication. But now